In TypeScript, you can use the `as` keyword to assert a type, and specify the type as a type guard. This technique is called "type assertion" or "type casting".

Here's an example:
```typescript
let value: string | number = 'hello'; // value can be either string or number

if (typeof value === 'string') {
  value = value as string; // assert that value is a string
  // now TypeScript knows that value is a string
  console.log(value); // okay, type is string
} else {
  value = value as number; // assert that value is a number
  // now TypeScript knows that value is a number
  console.log(value); // okay, type is number
}
```
In this example, we use the `as` keyword to assert that the value is a `string` or a `number`, depending on the condition. This tells TypeScript that, even though the compile-time type of `value` is a union type (`string | number`), we know that at runtime, it will only be one of those types.

TypeScript will not check the type at runtime; it's a compile-time optimization. The type checker will infer the type based on the type guard, and you'll get the correct type feedback in your IDE and with code completion.

Note that this is different from simply using `value = <string>value;`, which is called a "type cast" and is more of a hint to the compiler rather than a definitive truth. The `as` keyword provides a stronger guarantee to the type system.

When you use type assertions, make sure to use them judiciously and only when you have a solid understanding of the type system and the specific use case. Overusing type assertions can lead to type-related issues and maintenance headaches.

